    <header style="text-align: center; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
      <h1>Uses</h1>
      <p class="text-muted">Hardware, software, and the tools I keep around.</p>
      <p class="text-muted" style="font-size: 0.875rem;">Last updated: June 16, 2026</p>
    </header>

    <div class="card" style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <pre><code>$ uname -a
FreeBSD homefw 15.0-RELEASE-p5 FreeBSD 15.0-RELEASE-p5 amd64
$ cat ~/.workflow
edit:    nvim
shell:   zsh
mux:     tmux
term:    alacritty
wm:      niri
keys:    glove80</code></pre>

      <h2>Hardware</h2>

      <h3>Keyboards</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Glove80</strong> (MoErgo): primary daily driver. Split, columnar, contoured. My
            <a href="https://github.com/mvivirito/glove80-config" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">layout</a> is on GitHub.</li>
        <li><strong>Advantage360 Professional</strong> (Kinesis): travel keyboard with ZMK firmware. Config is
            <a href="https://github.com/mvivirito/advantage360" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">here</a>.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Workstation</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Threadripper 1950X desktop</strong>: 64 GB RAM, RTX 4080. Proxmox at the host level; a NixOS VM I call <strong>nixie-vm</strong> runs with full RTX 4080 passthrough. That's where the local AI lives, <strong>Ollama</strong> on the GPU and <strong>OpenWebUI</strong> in a container on the host (more <a href="#local-ai">below</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>ThinkPad X1 Nano</strong> (personal): NixOS, same flake as the desktop.</li>
        <li><strong>ASUS Zephyrus G16</strong> with an RTX 4090: NixOS, same flake. The machine that games and records.</li>
        <li>Two <strong>MacBooks</strong> (work + personal) managed with <strong>Nix Darwin</strong>, sharing the same flake as the Linux machines.</li>
        <li>Two displays, vertical arrangement, not horizontal.</li>
        <li>Wired ethernet wherever practical. Wifi is for visitors.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Audio</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Closed-back headphones for focus work.</li>
        <li>A small XLR mic on a boom arm for calls and the rare YouTube recording.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Operating Systems</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>FreeBSD 15.0-RELEASE</strong> (pkgbase) on the <a href="homelab">edge router</a> and on a small fleet of long-uptime hosts. ZFS root, base-system everything.</li>
        <li><strong>NixOS 24.11</strong> across the entire fleet, the Threadripper desktop, both laptops, the Proxmox-hosted server VMs, and (via Nix Darwin) the MacBooks. One flake spans all of them. Declarative, reproducible, and the closest thing to "it just works" once you've climbed the learning curve. (See <a href="articles/why-i-run-nixos">why</a>.)</li>
        <li><strong>Proxmox VE</strong> as the hypervisor under most of it.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Desktop &amp; Window Management</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Niri</strong> on the Linux machines: a scrolling-tiling Wayland compositor. Windows live on an infinite horizontal strip instead of being crammed into a grid, and it suits the ultrawide perfectly.</li>
        <li><strong>Dank Material Shell</strong> for the bar, launcher, notifications, and clipboard history. Frosted-glass, Tokyo Night, keyboard-first.</li>
        <li><strong>Aerospace</strong> for tiling on the MacBooks, with <strong>Hammerspoon</strong> hot-swapping layouts when the ultrawide gets plugged in.</li>
        <li><strong>KDE Plasma</strong> on nixie-vm, the one box I drive as a full desktop (it streams, see below).</li>
        <li><strong>Kanata</strong> remaps Caps Lock to Esc / Super on every machine. The single best ergonomics change I've made.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Editor &amp; Terminal</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Neovim</strong> with a small Lua config. Treesitter for highlighting, Telescope for fuzzy navigation, and LSPs for the languages I touch most (nixd, pyright, the TypeScript and Lua servers). Nothing exotic.</li>
        <li><strong>VS Code</strong> when a project wants a mouse or a debugger. I don't pretend otherwise.</li>
        <li><strong>Alacritty</strong> as the terminal, with <strong>Kitty</strong> as a fallback: GPU-accelerated, Rust-fast, JetBrainsMono Nerd Font, Tokyo Night. tmux handles tabs and splits.</li>
        <li><strong>tmux</strong> for persistent sessions on remote hosts. SSH disconnects shouldn't take work with them.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Shell &amp; CLI</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Zsh</strong> with oh-my-zsh (the <code>fishy</code> theme) and vi-mode. Not much more than that, a fast prompt beats a fancy one.</li>
        <li><strong>zoxide</strong> for jumping around the filesystem, <strong>eza</strong> in place of <code>ls</code>, <strong>direnv</strong> for per-project environments.</li>
        <li><strong>ripgrep</strong>, <strong>fd</strong>, <strong>fzf</strong>, <strong>bat</strong>, <strong>jq</strong>, <strong>sd</strong>, <strong>delta</strong>, <strong>dust</strong>, <strong>duf</strong>. The boring-modern stack of grep/find/sed/diff replacements.</li>
        <li><strong>git</strong>, of course. Plus <strong>lazygit</strong> for the moments my hands want a TUI.</li>
        <li><strong>btop</strong> and <strong>procs</strong> for "what is this box doing right now": see also the <a href="articles/top-10-tui-apps">TUI apps post</a>.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="local-ai">Local AI</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ollama</strong> on <strong>nixie-vm</strong>, the NixOS VM with the RTX 4080 passed through (CUDA build). A rotating set of local models: <strong>qwen2.5</strong> (14B and 32B), <strong>qwen2.5-coder</strong>, <strong>deepseek-r1</strong>, <strong>phi4</strong>, and <strong>gemma3</strong>.</li>
        <li><strong>OpenWebUI</strong> in a container on the Proxmox host, pointed at that Ollama. It's the ChatGPT-shaped front door to the LAN, so anyone in the house can use the local models from a browser without touching a terminal.</li>
        <li><strong>Claude Code</strong> (this CLI) for the heavier agentic work, code, ops, and the vault automation below.</li>
        <li><strong>Handy</strong> (a Tauri push-to-talk app) with <strong>whisper.cpp</strong> for dictation. Hold a key, talk, get text.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Second Brain: Telegram + Obsidian</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Obsidian</strong> over a folder of plain Markdown, synced across every machine with <strong>Syncthing</strong>. No proprietary store, just files.</li>
        <li>A Telegram bot, <strong>@NixieVMBot</strong>, is the capture inbox. Text, voice memos (transcribed on-box with whisper.cpp), photos, and files I send it land in the vault from wherever I am.</li>
        <li><strong>Claude Agent SDK</strong> timers on nixie-vm keep it tended: a morning briefing at 6, a midday pulse at noon, a night ingest-and-reflect at 10, and a deeper review on Sunday mornings.</li>
        <li>The vault auto-commits to git every 30 minutes and syncs to Google Drive nightly with <strong>rclone</strong>. Capture should be frictionless; durability shouldn't be a chore.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Network &amp; Homelab</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>FreeBSD pf router</strong> at the edge: the heart of the network. <a href="articles/freebsd-pf-router">Build post</a>, or <a href="homelab">tour the setup</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>unbound</strong> for recursive DNS, with DNSSEC validation and a small blocklist.</li>
        <li><strong>WireGuard</strong> for road-warrior VPN back into the LAN. (<a href="articles/freebsd-wireguard">Setup post</a>.)</li>
        <li><strong>Real, native IPv6</strong> via DHCPv6-PD from the ISP. (<a href="articles/freebsd-ipv6-router">How</a>.)</li>
        <li><strong>Managed L2 switch</strong> for VLANs to the IoT and quarantine networks.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Servers &amp; Storage</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Proxmox VE</strong> on a single homelab box hosting most of the VMs.</li>
        <li><strong>NixOS VMs</strong> for everything that runs more than a handful of services.</li>
        <li><strong>ZFS</strong> everywhere: for the boot environments alone.</li>
        <li><strong>ZFS send/recv</strong> to a remote pool for offsite backups. (<a href="articles/zfs-send-recv-replication">Replication script</a>.)</li>
        <li><strong>Prometheus + Grafana + Alertmanager</strong> for monitoring. (<a href="articles/prometheus-grafana-monitoring">How it's wired</a>.)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Gaming &amp; Streaming</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Sunshine</strong> on nixie-vm with <strong>Moonlight</strong> clients: the GPU-passthrough VM doubles as a stream host, so games and a full desktop reach the laptops and the couch.</li>
        <li><strong>Steam</strong> with Proton-GE, plus <strong>Lutris</strong> and <strong>Heroic</strong>, on the Zephyrus G16. <strong>RetroArch</strong> for the back catalog.</li>
        <li><strong>OBS Studio</strong> and <strong>gpu-screen-recorder</strong> (NVENC) when something needs capturing.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Languages I Reach For</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Bash / Shell</strong>: for glue, ops scripts, and "just enough automation".</li>
        <li><strong>Python</strong>: for anything past 50 lines of shell.</li>
        <li><strong>Go</strong>: for tools that need to be a single static binary.</li>
        <li><strong>JavaScript / TypeScript</strong> (Node 22): for the web side of things, this site included.</li>
        <li><strong>Nix expressions</strong>: for the configuration that defines everything else.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Browser &amp; Day-to-Day</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Firefox</strong> with a handful of containers and uBlock Origin.</li>
        <li>Notes, journal, and drafts live in the <a href="#local-ai">Obsidian vault</a> above, never in a tool I can't export from.</li>
        <li><strong>1Password</strong> for secrets, with the CLI wired into my shell for the scripted bits.</li>
        <li><strong>Telegram</strong> and <strong>Discord</strong> for chat; an RSS reader for keeping up with people, not algorithmic feeds.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Things I've Stopped Using</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Heavyweight router GUIs (OPNsense, pfSense). Both fine, both more abstraction than I want.</li>
        <li>Heavyweight prompts and terminal frameworks. Alacritty and a plain zsh prompt cover it.</li>
        <li>Most Electron apps. The ones I keep are kept reluctantly.</li>
        <li>Managed cloud Kubernetes for personal projects. Bare metal teaches more.</li>
        <li>Trying to learn ten things at once. Pick one and go deep.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Influences</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The <a href="https://www.freebsd.org/doc/handbook/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FreeBSD Handbook</a>: what good documentation looks like.</li>
        <li>Brendan Gregg's performance work: methodologies that survive vendor cycles.</li>
        <li>Derek Sivers' <a href="https://sive.rs/nowff" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">/now movement</a>: the inspiration for my <a href="now">/now page</a>.</li>
      </ul>

